observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

Require the GSO to maintain property cards using the prescribed format which are necessary to support the accuracy and reliability of the balance of PPE account in the financial statements and reconcile with the accounting records;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to maintain PPELC for each category of PPE and transfer the Building account from the Trust Fund book to the General Fund valued at ₱827,546.00 and provide the corresponding depreciation costs;
Require the GSO to conduct physical inventory and render report thereon within the prescribed period and regularly monitor the progress of the inventory taking; and
Require the GSO to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant to initiate compliance with the guidelines and procedures for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts.

To clean up the books of accounts of Due to NGAs which found to be non-moving or outstanding, we recommended that Management:

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with the DOH and DSWD to return the unutilized balance of ₱5,912.32 and ₱4,916.81, respectively; 
Direct the Municipal Accountant to conduct verification, analysis, and validation of the balances of the Due to NGAs accounts, particularly those fund transfers with incomplete documentation and determine the status of programs, projects and activities for which funds were received; 
Direct the Municipal Accountant to maintain complete records of fund transfers received from various NGAs to facilitate reconciliation of the balances of Due to NGAs account with the balances of concerned source agencies, and effect the necessary adjustments, as warranted; and
Conduct verification and validation of the proper agency for remittance of the ante-mortem fees totaling ₱146,194.44.

We recommended that Management:
Establish a designated stockroom to ensure the proper storage and safekeeping of procured inventory items;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Record all acquisitions of inventories to their appropriate Inventory accounts and recognize the corresponding expenses upon receipt of SSMI supported with RIS from the GSO- Designate;
Maintain SLCs for each class of inventory procured;
Require the GSO- Designate to:
Conduct physical inventory of supplies and materials on a semestral basis and submit a report thereon to the Municipal Accountant and the Audit Team for reference in audit; and
Prepare and maintain SCs, RIS, and SSMI to properly account the receipt, issuances and balances of inventory items.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Budget Officer to:
Reconcile the difference in appropriations in the final budget per audit as against the final budget per SCBAA by cross-referencing budgeted amounts in the original budget against any authorized changes made thereon through the enacted supplemental budgets;
Stop the practice of treating unexpended balances of appropriations for MOOE as continuing appropriations. Instead, revert the same to the unappropriated surplus of the general fund at the end of the fiscal year;
Analyze transactions affecting the balance of continuing appropriations and make the necessary adjustments on the discrepancy noted between the ending balance in CY 2023 and forwarded balance in CY 2024;
Always include any depreciation expense recognized during the year as a valid reconciling item under “basis differences” in the reconciliation statement of the SCBAA and SFPer;
Ensure proper charging of expenses in the appropriate budget class to avoid invalid reconciling items;
Exert utmost effort to reconcile the difference in the actual amounts of MOOE with the MOOE recognized in the SFPer amounting to ₱108,666.27 by reviewing and comparing all charges posted in RAAO-MOOE with expenses recorded in the books of accounts and disclose the details of reconciling items in the NTFS to provide reliable information to the users of financial statements;
Reconcile the accounting records with the records of the Budget Office monthly or as frequent as practicable so that any resulting reconciling items and or discrepancies could be immediately identified and/or corrected; and
Provide disclosures on the face of the SCBAA and/or in the NTFS for the changes in the original budget and material discrepancies between the budget and actual amounts to enhance transparency of the LGU’s financial statements.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the BAC to consolidate the office supplies requirement for a two-month period and procure them through public bidding, in case of unavailability in the PS-DBM, ensuring adherence to the conditions set forth by law before considering alternative modes of procurement;
Require the BAC to properly accomplish the APP, particularly to indicate the mode of procurement for each procurement activity;
Instruct all offices and department heads to submit their PPMP for consolidation into APP by the BAC;
Direct the GSO designate to safekeep undistributed procured items and maintain record of inventory for monitoring and accountability purposes and issue the necessary RIS and ICS for every issuance to the requesting office; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to thoroughly check the completeness of the supporting documents as before certification thereof.

We recommended that Management instruct the:
Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, to discontinue the practice of granting cash advances to employees for the conduct of events or activities of the LGU. Instead, payments should be made directly to the supplier or trainers through the issuance of checks for proper withholding of taxes.
Municipal Budget Officer and the BAC, that if meals, snacks and supplies pertain to events and/or activities regularly conducted by the LGU, they must be included in the APP and purchase the same through applicable procurement method;
Municipal Accountant, BAC and other accountable officers involved to submit the lacking documents identified for further evaluation of the Audit Team;
Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Accountant, to initiate the refund of irregular expenditures incurred by the accountable officers amounting to ₱636,815.35, if warranted; and
Municipal Accountant to thoroughly review all supporting documents prior to certifying the completeness and accuracy of liquidation documents in order to strengthen the internal control system.

We recommended that Management submit valid justification/s on the foregoing deficiencies noted in the procurement through SVP.
We also recommended that Management direct the BAC to:
Ensure that the APP is readily available in all stages of procurement to properly examine its significance in facilitating the efficient discharge of government functions;
Ensure the preparation of a BAC resolution recommending and justifying to the HoPE the use of an alternative method of procurement, as well as obtaining the approval of the HoPE prior to resorting to an alternative method of procurement;
Ensure that the delegation has been properly authorized by the BAC through a resolution approved by the HoPE, if they opt to delegate to the end-user or appropriate committee the canvassing or serving of RFQ;
Update or revise the RFQ form to include the suppliers PhilGEPS Registration Number and require them to supply the said information along with their price quotation;
Make the necessary postings in the PHilGEPS, for procurements above ₱50,000.00, to maintain transparency and encourage fair competition in the procurement process; and
Require from the supplier the submission of documents necessary in the use of alternative method of SVP.
We further recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Submit the lacking documents and ensure that all the documentary requirements are complete before certifying thereto; and
See to it that all disbursements involving procurement of goods and services undertaken through alternative method of procurement are duly supported with complete documentary requirements.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking documents necessary to support the subject transactions and for further evaluation. Additionally, the Municipal Accountant must thoroughly verify the propriety and completeness of all supporting documents prior to certifying them;
Immediately stop bypassing the procurement process and ensure that all procurement activities strictly comply with the provisions of Republic Act No. 9184 and its Revised IRR. This is essential to prevent irregular, unnecessary, or unauthorized expenditures and to safeguard public funds;
Submit all purchase requests to the BAC for consolidation and to ensure that all procurement activities follow the appropriate steps in accordance with applicable laws and regulations;
Strengthen internal controls by strictly prohibiting advance payments for goods or services unless explicitly authorized by law and ensure that payments are made only upon delivery, inspection, and acceptance of goods or services;
Require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, to initiate the immediate refund of the overpayment made to the service provider; and
Ensure that all contracts, memoranda of agreement, and related documents entered into by the Municipality are properly authorized through a resolution or ordinance by the Sangguniang Bayan, and that only duly authorized officials sign such agreements in accordance with their legal authority.

We recommended that Management:

Stop the granting of GMA loan to employees of LGU due to the absence of availability of funds;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to immediately return the amount of ₱778,723.01 to the General Fund;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to transfer the amortization of loan in the TF as soon as amortization was deducted from the salaries of borrowers and to properly monitor the collection of loans receivable and update their individual records; and
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with the Office of the President or the concerned national government agency to verify if the remaining funds granted to the LGU for the “One Town One Project” in the amount of ₱250,000.00 is still subject to liquidation.  If yes, secure a copy of the MOA and cause the immediate liquidation thereof, otherwise, instruct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the account used in recording such assistance from Due to NGAs to Subsidy from NGAs.

4.9	We recommended that Management:
4.9.1	Require the GSO to maintain property cards using the prescribed format which are necessary to support the accuracy and reliability of the balance of PPE account in the financial statements and reconcile with the accounting records;
4.9.2	Instruct the Municipal Accountant to maintain PPELC for each category of PPE and transfer the Building account from the Trust Fund book to the General Fund valued at ₱827,546.00 and provide the corresponding depreciation costs;
4.9.3	Require the GSO to conduct physical inventory and render report thereon within the prescribed period and regularly monitor the progress of the inventory taking; and
4.9.4	Require the GSO to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant to initiate compliance with the guidelines and procedures for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain PPE Ledger Cards for each category of assets and Real Property Ledger Cards for land;


Require the General Services Officer (GSO)- Designate to maintain Property Cards per category of PPE which are necessary to support the accuracy and reliability of the balance of the PPE account in the financial statements;

Create an Inventory Committee and require the conduct of physical inventory and to render report thereon as required under Sections 266 and 269 of GAM, Volume I and to regularly monitor the progress of the inventory taking; and

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to submit General Ledger and Subsidiary Ledger pertaining to the PPE accounts in order to validate the balances.

We recommend that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit the 2020 and 2021 BRS of Cash in Bank-General Fund in order that errors or discrepancies on recorded amounts will be detected and adjusted in the books of accounts;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to maintain Subsidiary ledgers of all bank accounts maintained by the Agency for easy monitoring of the cash balances at the end of each month;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile their records every quarter or as often as needed pursuant to the above cited provisions to closely monitor the correctness of the balances; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to draw adjusting journal entries (AJE) to reflect the valid reconciling items in the books of accounts and identify the details of adjusting entries recorded amounting to ₱872,330.92 to verify if such adjusting entries are proper and accurate, otherwise, adjustments of affected accounts be made.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to maintain PPE Ledger Cards for each category of assets and Real Property Ledger Cards for land, and the GSO- Designate to maintain Property Cards per category of PPE which are necessary to support the accuracy and reliability of the balance of the PPE account in the financial statements;
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain Subsidiary Ledger per classification of PPE;
Direct the GSO- Designate to prepare and update each PAR every three years after issue or every time there is a change in accountability;
Require the Municipal Accountant to transfer the Buildings account to the General Fund with book value of ₱827,546.00 and to provide depreciation costs; and
Require the GSO to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant to initiate compliance with the guidelines and procedures for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to trace the details of the difference arising from the reconciliation of SCBAA and SFPe under Personnel Services and MOOE totaling ₱1,991,478.04 and ₱35,343.77, respectively;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer to maintain RAAOs and SAAOB, respectively, in support of the actual amounts in the SCBAA and the reconciliation with the amounts presented in the SFPe;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to provide adequate disclosure on the reconciling items presented in the reconciliation between actual amounts on a comparable basis in the SCBAA and in the SFPe; and
Instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to revert the unspent MOOE under 20% development fund to the unappropriated surplus subject for re-programming in the ensuing year.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Create an Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of public infrastructures specially the local road networks;



Instruct the General Services Officer - Designate to periodically render Report on Local Road Networks, and furnish copies to the concerned offices. Also, the Municipal Engineer should provide the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer – Designate with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain separate subsidiary ledgers for each individual road networks; and 

Ensure coordination among LGU Offices to properly implement the accounting and reporting guidelines on the Local Road Asset Management System.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Accountant to submit the complete documentary requirements as mentioned in COA Circular No. 2012-001 and Section 4 (6) of PD 1445;

Follow the rules and procedures under Small Value Procurement (SVP) in compliance with the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184 and Section 4 (6) of PD 1445;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to stop from using Reimbursement Expense Receipt (RER), instead require the submission of official receipts from supplier as evidence of receipt of payment to ensure that all transactions are properly documented and the funds disbursed are actually received by the payees; and

Strictly comply with the rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances as provided for under COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997.

We have recommended that Management:
Instruct the MSWDO to register all recipient associations in DOLE to obtain legal personality and officers who would be responsible and accountable for its operations;
Submit the required documents stated in COA Circular 2007-001 to support the validity and legality of the transaction;
Instruct the recipient NGO’s/ POs to maintain and submit financial/ accounting records of the funds and other physical status reports of the project;
Strictly monitor the remittance of the amortization of 33.33% of the  total seed capital assistance received by each association for 2 years through designated banks, and consider charging of interest to delayed remittance of fund to  control and enforce payment of amortization within the agreed period; and
Ensure that Seed Capital Assistance would be completely rolled-back to DSWD on June 2017 and new set of associations would be able to avail the same assistance under the SEA Kaunlaran Scheme.
